#Day-72
Canary Deployments with Argo Rollouts (setWeight) 

Canary deployments allow you to release new application versions gradually, reducing risk and protecting users from widespread failures.
In this example, I explored Argo Rollouts using the setWeight strategy, where traffic is shifted in steps (20% â†’ 40% â†’ 60% â†’ 80% â†’ 100%) with optional pause points for validation.

ğŸ”‘ Key insights:
setWeight controls traffic exposure, not just pod count
With NodePort or ClusterIP, traffic is split indirectly by scaling Canary pods and relying on Kubernetes Service load balancing
For production-grade traffic control, a cloud LoadBalancer, Ingress, or service mesh (NGINX, ALB, Istio) is recommended for precise routing and observability

ğŸŒ Real-world use case:
 Imagine deploying a new payment service version:
Start with 20% of users
Monitor errors, latency, and business metrics
Pause if needed
Gradually expand once confidence is built
This approach is especially valuable for mission-critical systems, where safety matters more than speed.

